However, many health care experts, focusing on Somali women’s health care seem to cite their cultural norms and beliefs as the reason why nearly most Somali women are not utilizing their health care services which is convenient and available for them.

Somali women should be in the position to make their own choices and allow their cultural beliefs and values to be more inclusive to each individual’s sexual orientation and choice.

If Somali women are educated early enough on their sexual and reproductive health, family planning has a greater possibility of being recognized and extensively practiced.

When we allow our social, religious, cultural and ethnic beliefs to confine us and possibly shape decision-making that pertains to our health especially for our women, it ultimately contradicts and its primary purpose.

It is time for Somali women to be recognized fully and be given everything that is rightfully theirs to enhance their economic status, mental growth as well have a stable mental health.

How confident are you in your cultural beliefs? Do you think they influence your health or make a position when making the appropriate decisions that are significant for your mental and physical health care wise?
